In the early morning at 3:00 AM the following day, after the excitement of the previous day has subsided, the priests force the god-man to carry a dobei (a lump of rice cake imbued with all impurities) on his back. They then pelt him with pebbles made from small branches fashioned from {{ill|peach|ja|桃}} and {{ill|willow|ja|柳}}, expelling him from the shrine grounds. The god-man, having been bound with all sins and defilements, discards the dobei into the dark and departs without looking back, while the priests complete the ritual of exorcising misfortune by burying the discarded dobei in the ground<ref name="navi" />. This ritual is called {{nihongo|Yonaoi Shinji|よなおいしんじ}}, and is regarded as the most important ceremony of the festival<ref name="naoi">{{Cite web|url=http://www.city.inazawa.aichi.jp/miryoku/bunka/kenshitei/1002914.html |title=Prefectural Designated Cultural Property: Kounomiya's Naooi Festival|publisher=Inazawa City|date=2019-01-29 |accessdate=2024-01-13}}</ref>. Moreover, the pebbles hurled at the god-man during his expulsion are reduced to ash and are incorporated into the dobei for the following year.

The related events of the festival take place over approximately half a month, from the 2nd day of the lunar new year (旧暦正月2日) to the 14th day (旧暦正月14日).
{{-}}

